			<h3 ><a href="#p144021">Re: 85 Raiding Enchanter- Specialisation</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=144021#p144021"><img src="./styles/prosilver/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4819">Moriquend</a></strong> &raquo; Aug 25th, '09, 15:10 </p>

			

			<div class="content"><blockquote><div><cite>Sunaeri wrote:</cite>I still look at it from the side of which spell line can I least afford to fizzle.  Even on raids, that is still mez.   Fizzling nukes doesn't kill me.  On raids if I go down, you know my healer is next, and then the group.  There are so many options for increasing mana regen and conserving mana, but very little that decreases fizzles.</div></blockquote><br /><br />I think there is some merit to the logic of looking at specialization from the standpoint of &quot;what spell, if fizzeld, would present the greatest immediate danger to me and my group/raid&quot;.  However, I'm not sure that single target mezzes (which are conjuration) are necessarily the most dangerous spells to fizzle, anymore.<br /><br />This is due, in large part, to the existence of Beguilder's Directed Banishment, though I suppose it depends on how you typically handle loose adds.  I almost always banish mobs first, then mez second.  On rootable mobs, this practice virtually eliminates any danger that would result from the first attempt to mez fizzling (unless, of coarse, you fling the mob into melee range of someone, but that's usually avoided easily enough).  Even on mobs that are immune to root, the knockback buys you enough time that, with single-target mez being as fast-cast as it is, you can usually afford to fizzle mez once and still get the second attempt to mez off before the mob can kill anyone.  Where the potential danger of fizzling single-target mezzes comes in again, is when you get multiple adds simultaneously, but those adds are not grouped closely enough to lead off with a PBAE mez.  In this case, you won't have the luxury of being able to banish first then mez second on every mob, due to the refresh timer on BDB.  The best you could do is banish every other mob during initial lockdown (i.e. banish and mez mob01, then mez mob02, then banish and mez mob03, ...), so fizzles could be deadly in these situations.  However, I should note that, unless someone is doing something wrong (or you're doing an event where mezzes are dispelled every so often), the only time when fizzling a mez is dangerous is on initial lockdown.  Once a mob has been mezzed the first time, you should be able to refresh that mez early enough that you get the mob remezzed before it wakes up, even if you get a couple fizzles and/or resists.<br /><br />One could argue that the most dangerous spell we could fizzle is a PBAE mez (or a PBAE stun) as these spells are typically used in situations where we are CCing several mobs at once.  In the case of PBAE mezzes, this definately used to be true.  I say &quot;used to&quot; because there used to be a very small window between the time your PBAE mez spell gem refreshed and the time your PBAE mez wore off.  A fizzle at the wrong time could mean several mobs woke up simultaneously and things would get hairy fast.  Nowadays, with Mez Mastery 3, we have more of a cushion to play with, so we can survive a fizzle every once in a while.  Something to consider, though, is that, while fizzling a PBAE mez (in a situation where you are chaining PBAE mezzes) is usually more dangerous than fizzling a single-target mez (in situations where you are using it), there are generally far more situations where you using single target mez to CC 1 or 2 mobs than there are where you are chaining PBAE mezzes.  So, if you look at it from the standpoint of &quot;how many potential deaths will I have eliminated, in the long run, by choosing one spec over the other&quot;, it's probably a toss-up between conjuration (single-target mezzes) and divination (PBAE mezzes and stuns).<br /><br />You could also argue that, in some cases, the most dangerous spell to fizzle would be charm (which is alteration).  Afterall, in many situations where you are casting charm, you are dealing with a mob that has been buffed and geared to do more damage than your average mob.  Of coarse, fizzling charm is only dangerous if charm is the spell you are using to regain control over that loose mob.  In lots of cases, it won't be, as banishing or mezzing the mob and then charming is a safer way to deal with it, assuming the mob can be rooted/mezzed.  However, if the mob is immune to both root and mez, then getting the mob recharmed ASAP may be the only way to keep it from killing you and/or your group/raid.  Unlike mezzes, charm is not something that can be refreshed early, so you can't reduce the risk to something that only occurs once, on initial lockdown.  In these situations, (i.e. the ones where charm is your only option for regaining control over the mob) you are looking at potential danger each and every time you cast charm, which may be several times during the encounter, depending on duration of the encounter and how often charm breaks early.  Also, charm casts more slowly than mez, so the potential of death is greater in the first place.  Where you might survive a single round of attacks when fizzling and then sticking a mez, your chances of surviving two to three rounds of attacks while fizzling and then trying to channel another attempt at charm are much smaller.  But, again, you have to factor in how often you find yourself in this type of situation.  9 times out of 10, you can use mez/banish to regain control of a mob that broke charm, plus you are probably using charm in fewer events than you are using mez in to begin with.<br /><br />In the end, I guess it comes down to your playstyle.  For me, I'd say the danger due to a fizzle balances out pretty evenly, when you factor in frequency, between single-target mezzes (conjuration), PBAE mezzes/stuns (divination), and charm (alteration).  So, while this is a factor I look at, there isn't enough of a difference to use this as the only basis of comparison (though it does pretty much eliminate evocation from consideration, in my book).  I also look at the mana costs (over time) of the spells I am using from each category and try to weigh the importance of having the mana to keep casting that spell (as necessary) to the raid.</div>

			

		</div>

		
